<br>
2) When one actually starts taking logs, and actually counting resists, one finds that rains are not resisting nearly as often as most mages assume.  They get a run of resists, courtesy of the random number generator, and then assume that resist rate is normal.  Again, read the thread I referenced earlier for <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">actual</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> resist rates.<br>
<br>
3) Rains are still a good deal, for either conjuration <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">or</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> evocation specialized mages.  Again, the referenced thread is a comparison between <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Sirocco</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Shock of Fiery Blades</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Sirocco</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> comes out looking good.<br>
<br>
4) Because hate is proportional to damage and decays over time, rains cause less aggro than doing the same amount of damage using a single nuke.  High DPS <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">and</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> low aggro?  What else do you want from life?  A baby's arm holding an apple?<br>
<br>
Do the research, do the math, as I and other mages have, and you will find that rain spells, as they exist now, are a very good deal.<br>
<br>
